Preface:
x86-64 | Unix/linux etc. | C/C++  
Difficulty: 2.0 | Quality: 4.5

Description:
Find a real key and recover a flag
  
# Basics
We recieve `crackme`, determining the file as to be below:
{{< highlight bash >}}
torry@twooo:cm$ file crackme
crackme: ELF 64-bit LSB pie executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, not stripped
{{< /highlight >}}
We can note that the binary is not stripped, which will make it simple to analyse and debug.
  
Executing the binary we can understand its simple behaviour:
{{< highlight bash >}}
torry@twooo:cm$ ./crackme
Usage: ./crackme FLAG
torry@twooo:cm$ ./crackme FLAG
Wrong flag
{{< /highlight >}}
The binary prints its usage, expecting a CLI argument of the FLAG, inputting "FLAG" as a test string gives us "Wrong flag"

Using `strings` we find points of interest. 
{{< highlight bash >}}
Usage: ./crackme FLAG
Wrong flag
sup3r_s3cr3t_k3y_1337
You found a flag! %s
{{< /highlight >}}

Simply by using "sup3r_s3cr3t_k3y_1337" as our input we find it not to be the flag. We can also use `ltrace` and observe that this is not as trivial as a strcmp() between our input and the said flag. We also note the use of the `%s` specifier which is used in the printf() function, this output is our current goal to retrieve the flag.

# Patch2Loose
We can attempt to patch the binary to simply call printf() and hopefully print our flag. We can do this by using GDB as below, also note we can simply `break main` as the binary is not stripped and still includes its symbols.
{{< highlight bash >}}
torry@twooo:cm$ gdb -q file -ex "break main" -ex "run"
[snip]
Breakpoint 1, 0x0000555555555169 in main ()
{{< /highlight >}}
At this point we can print the next N number of instructions and locate where the printf function call is inside the program:
 {{< highlight bash >}}
torry@twooo:cm$ (gdb) x/100i $rip
[snip]
   0x55555555519c <main+55>:    call   0x555555555030 <puts@plt>
[snip]
   0x5555555551bc <main+87>:    call   0x555555555040 <strlen@plt>
[snip]
   0x5555555551ce <main+105>:   call   0x555555555030 <puts@plt>
[snip]
   0x55555555534b <main+486>:   call   0x555555555060 <printf@plt>
{{< /highlight >}}
Skimming all the `call` instructions, we can see what functions are being called and ideate the flow of the program, we know the binary will put a usage and an incorrect message, which we can see above, we also see a strlen(), which we can guess to be a basic check of the flag we can pull apart later. Importantly, we see what we believe to be our printf() function printing the flag.
  
We can further use GDB to set the address of our next instruction to the effective address before the call to printf(), 
{{< highlight bash >}}
(gdb) set $rip = 0x55555555533f
(gdb) c
Continuing.
You found a flag!
*** stack smashing detected ***: terminated
{{< /highlight >}}
By overwriting $RIP, we can successfully make the call to `printf`. However the expected output we saw in our strings analysis of the specifier `%s` is missing. This tells us that the program does not as simply print the flag: yes or no, but that we have skipped critical execution flow that sets the value. (and also segfaults) It is difficult to know without further analysis, but we can assume that our input must meet further requirements to correctly set values of which we dont immediately know.

# Analysis
Using IDA we can decompile the main function as below:
{{< highlight c >}}
int __cdecl main(int argc, const char **argv, const char **envp)
{
  int i; // [rsp+10h] [rbp-90h]
  int j; // [rsp+14h] [rbp-8Ch]
  int v6[30]; // [rsp+20h] [rbp-80h]
  unsigned __int64 v7; // [rsp+98h] [rbp-8h]

  v7 = __readfsqword(0x28u);
  if ( argc == 1 )
  {
    puts("Usage: ./crackme FLAG");
    return 1;
  }
  else if ( strlen(argv[1]) == 21 )
  {
    for ( i = 0; i <= 20; ++i )
      *((_BYTE *)&v6[24] + i) = aSup3rS3cr3tK3y[i] - 34;
    v6[0] = 55;
    v6[1] = 63;
    v6[2] = 47;
    v6[3] = 118;
    v6[4] = 43;
    v6[5] = 98;
    v6[6] = 40;
    v6[7] = 33;
    v6[8] = 52;
    v6[9] = 15;
    v6[10] = 119;
    v6[11] = 98;
    v6[12] = 72;
    v6[13] = 39;
    v6[14] = 117;
    v6[15] = 8;
    v6[16] = 86;
    v6[17] = 106;
    v6[18] = 104;
    v6[19] = 78;
    v6[20] = 104;
    for ( j = 0; j <= 20; ++j )
    {
      if ( (char)(argv[1][j] ^ *((_BYTE *)&v6[24] + j)) != v6[j] )
      {
        puts("Wrong flag");
        return 1;
      }
    }
    printf("You found a flag! %s\n", argv[1]);
    return 0;
  }
  else
  {
    puts("Wrong flag");
    return 1;
  }
}
{{< /highlight >}}

Reading through main, we can note and gather a few observations:  

The code will print it usage if argc is equal to 1, else it will check if the string length of the first argument is equal to 21, if not it will print the wrong flag message.  
  
If the first argument is equal to 21, it will enter 2 loops,

The first loop "initialises" the value in  `aSup3rS3cr3tK3y` ("sup3r_s3cr3t_k3y_1337" this is also 21 characters!) at index 24 of the `v6` array, however it will subtract `34` from each byte.

The second loop iterates through our first argument in an if statement, checking if each byte XOR the initialised second half of the `v6` array is equal to the bytes in the first half of the `v6` array (visible above), if they match, it will print the win message along with our first argument, else print the fail message.
  
To simplify, we can imagine these operations just parsing a single byte:
{{< highlight bash >}}
input = 0x66
secret_key = 0x73

v6_1 = 0x37
v6_2 = secret_key - 0x22

if input ^ v6_2 == v6_1
	win! 
{{< /highlight >}}

Referencing the title of the challenge, we discover the real key is not "sup3r_s3cr3t_k3y_1337", however each byte of the string -34 as a XOR key.

# Solve
To solve, we can simply calculate the second half of the v6 array and XOR it with the first half, this should retrieve our flag. We can write a simple python program to do this.
{{< highlight bash >}}
flag = ""
aSup3rS3cr3tK3y = "sup3r_s3cr3t_k3y_1337"

v6_p1 = [55, 63, 47, 118, 43, 98, 40, 33, 52, 15, 119, 98, 72, 39, 117, 8, 86, 106, 104, 78, 104]
v6_p2 = []

for char in aSup3rS3cr3tK3y:
    v6_p2.append((ord(char) - 34))

for i in range(len(v6_p1)):
    flag += chr(v6_p1[i] ^ v6_p2[i])

print(flag)
{{< /highlight >}}
This outputs `flag{_y0u_f0und_key_}`, and we can confirm this is the flag by running the binary with this as our input:
{{< highlight bash >}}
torry@twooo:cm$ ./crackme `python3 solve.py`
You found a flag! flag{_y0u_f0und_key_}
{{< /highlight >}}
Success! Thats the flag!
